"{\"continue\":{\"rvcontinue\":\"20151125175830|692436180\",\"continue\":\"||\"},\"warnings\":{\"main\":{\"*\":\"Subscribe to the mediawiki-api-announce mailing list at <https://lists.wikimedia.org/mailman/listinfo/mediawiki-api-announce> for notice of API deprecations and breaking changes. Use [[Special:ApiFeatureUsage]] to see usage of deprecated features by your application.\"},\"revisions\":{\"*\":\"Because \\\"rvslots\\\" was not specified, a legacy format has been used for the output. This format is deprecated, and in the future the new format will always be used.\"}},\"query\":{\"normalized\":[{\"from\":\"Jason_Chaffetz\",\"to\":\"Jason Chaffetz\"}],\"pages\":{\"17860391\":{\"pageid\":17860391,\"ns\":0,\"title\":\"Jason Chaffetz\",\"revisions\":[{\"timestamp\":\"2015-12-18T02:11:43Z\",\"contentformat\":\"text/x-wiki\",\"contentmodel\":\"wikitext\",\"*\":\"{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2015}}\\n{{lead too short|date=October 2015}}\\n{{Infobox officeholder\\n|name          = Jason Chaffetz\\n|image         = Jason Chaffetz, official portrait, 111th Congress.jpg\\n|office1       = Chairman of the [[United States House Committee on Oversight and Government Reform|House Committee on Oversight and Government Reform]]\\n|term_start1   = January 3, 2015\\n|term_end1     =\\n|predecessor1  = [[Darrell Issa]]\\n|successor1    =\\n|state2         = [[Utah]]\\n|district2      = {{ushr|Utah|3|3rd}}\\n|term_start2    = January 3, 2009\\n|term_end2      =\\n|predecessor2   = [[Chris Cannon]]\\n|successor2     =\\n|birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1967|3|26}}\\n|birth_place   = [[Los Gatos, California|Los Gatos]], [[California]], [[United States|U.S.]]\\n|death_date    =\\n|death_place   =\\n|party         = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] {{small|(Before 1990)}}<br>[[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] {{small|(1990\\u2013present)}}\\n|spouse        = Julie Marie Johnson {{small|(1991\\u2013present)}}\\n|children      = 3\\n|alma_mater    = [[Brigham Young University]]\\n|religion      = [[The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]] ([[Mormon]])\\n|website       = {{URL|http://chaffetz.house.gov|House website}}\\n}}\\n'''Jason E Chaffetz''' ({{IPAc-en|\\u02c8|t\\u0283|e\\u026a|f|\\u0268|t|s}}; born March 26, 1967) is the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. representative]] for {{ushr|UT|3}}, first elected in 2008. He is a member of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]]. \\n\\n== Early life and education ==\\nChaffetz was born in [[Los Gatos, California]], and was raised in [[Arizona]] and [[Colorado]] with his younger brother Alex.  His father, John A. Chaffetz, was [[Jewish]], and his mother, Margaret A. Wood,<ref>{{cite web |title=California Marriage Index, 1960\\u20131985 |url=https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:V6LM-Z2W}}</ref> was a [[Christian Scientist]]. Chaffetz converted from Judaism to [[Mormonism]] during his last year of college.<ref>{{cite web |first=J. J. |last=Goldberg |url=http://blogs.forward.com/jj-goldberg/123503/ |title=Meet Jewish Senators 14, 15 \\u2013 and 16? Plus: the House GOP's Jewish Mormon |publisher=''[[The Forward|The Jewish Daily Forward]]'' |date=January 15, 2010 |accessdate=November 18, 2011}}</ref> He attended [[Brigham Young University]] (BYU) on an athletic scholarship, and was the starting [[placekicker]] on the [[BYU Cougars football|BYU football]] team in 1988 and 1989. He still holds the BYU individual records for most [[extra point]]s attempted in a game, most extra points made in a game, and most consecutive extra points made in a game.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://byucougars.com/node/80772?ajax=1 |title=BYU Football Records |publisher=[[BYU Cougars|BYU Athletics]] |accessdate=November 18, 2011}}</ref> Chaffetz graduated from the [[BYU College of Fine Arts and Communications]] in 1989, with a [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]] in communications.<ref>{{cite web|title=Baccalaureate Degrees|url=https://archive.org/stream/commencementexer1990brig#page/54/mode/2up/search/chaffetz|website=Spring Commencement Exercises|publisher=Brigham Young University|pages=54|date=April 26, 1990}}</ref>\\n\\nWhile in college, Chaffetz was a [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]].  His father had previously been married to [[Kitty Dukakis|Kitty Dickson]], who afterward was married to the later [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] governor of Massachusetts, [[Michael Dukakis]]; Chaffetz's half-brother is former actor [[John Dukakis]].<ref name=\\\"NYT-7Jun2007\\\">{{cite news |first=Michael |last=Teitelbaum, |url=http://www.nytimes.com/cq/2007/06/07/cq_2852.html |title=Immigration Issue Again Draws In-House Rivals to Utah Lawmaker |publisher=''[[The New York Times]]'' |date= June 7, 2007 |accessdate=November 18, 2011}}</ref>  Despite their different political affiliations, Chaffetz remains close to his half-brother and the Dukakis family.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rollcall.com/issues/54_137/-35334-1.html |title=Chaffetz Found Red Out of the Blue |first=Jackie |last=Kucinich |date=June 1, 2009 |work=Roll Call |accessdate=October 12, 2015}}</ref>  While a student at BYU, Chaffetz was Utah co-chairman of Dukakis' [[1988 United States presidential election|1988 presidential campaign]].  After college, Chaffetz worked about a decade in [[public relations]] for a [[multi-level marketing]] company, [[Nu Skin|Nu Skin International]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Cottle|first1=Michelle|title=The Media's Best Friend|url=http://www.nationaljournal.com/magazine/2015/01/23/medias-best-friend|accessdate=February 15, 2015|work=National Journal Magazine|date=January 24, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Adrienne |last=Drell |title=Nu Skin recruiting pitch lures sellers \\u2013 and probers  |publisher=''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' |date=April 30, 1991 |accessdate=November 29, 2011 |page=16}}</ref>\\n\\n== Early political career ==\\nChaffetz became a Republican after meeting [[Ronald Reagan]], in 1990, when Reagan visited Chaffetz's employer, Nu Skin, as a motivational speaker. However, his political views had been drifting more to the right even while working for Dukakis.<ref>{{cite web |first=Kate |last=McNeil, |url=http://www.heraldextra.com/content/view/285061/1/ |title=3D: Chaffetz profile |publisher=''[[Daily Herald (Utah)|Herald Extra]]'' |date=October 18, 2008 |accessdate=November 18, 2011}}</ref>\\n\\nIn 2003, Chaffetz applied to be an agent in the [[United States Secret Service]] but was not accepted because \\\"better qualified applicants existed.\\\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Schmidt|first1=Michael S.|title=Senior Secret Service Official Proposed Embarrassing a Critic in Congress|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2015/10/01/us/politics/senior-secret-service-official-proposed-embarrassing-a-critic-in-congress-jason-chaffetz.html?hp&action=click&pgtype=Homepage&module=second-column-region&region=top-news&WT.nav=top-news|accessdate=October 1, 2015|publisher=New York Times|date=September 30, 2015}}</ref>\\n\\nIn 2004, Chaffetz was the campaign manager for Utah gubernatorial candidate [[Jon Huntsman, Jr.|Jon Huntsman]]. Huntsman won the race, and when he took office in January 2005, Chaffetz became Huntsman's chief of staff.<ref>{{cite web |first=Dan  |last=Harrie |url=http://www.stateline.org/live/ViewPage.action?siteNodeId=136&languageId=1&contentId=15892 |title=Huntsman ties his success as gov to Utah economy |publisher=Stateline: Pew Center on the States |date=January 4, 2005 |accessdate=November 18, 2011}}</ref> In November 2005, Chaffetz left that position to manage his own company, Maxtera Utah, a corporate communications and marketing company.\\n\\nIn 2006, Chaffetz was appointed by Huntsman as a trustee for [[Utah Valley University|Utah Valley State College]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hollingshead|first1=Todd|title=Chaffetz takes spot on UVSC trustee board|url=http://archive.sltrib.com/article.php?id=3882592&itype=NGPSID|website=Salt Lake Tribune|accessdate=May 18, 2015|date=May 31, 2006}}</ref> Chaffetz has also served as a member of the Highland City planning commission and as chairman for the Utah National Guard adjutant general review.\\n\\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\\n\\n===Chairmanship, House Oversight & Government Reform Committee===\\nIn November 2014, Chaffetz won a four-way race to become the chairman of the House Oversight & Government Reform Committee.  He was only the fifth Member of Congress in 89 years to become a full chairman after just three terms.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nationaljournal.com/magazine/the-media-s-best-friend-20150123 |title=The media's best friend |first=Michelle|last=Cottle|publisher=''National Journal''|date=January 24, 2015|accessdate=May 8, 2015}}</ref> He ran on a promise to emphasize reform.  \\u201cThe pitch I made to the steering committee is we really have to triangulate the problem if we\\u2019re actually going to get to reform,\\u201d Chaffetz told Politico. \\u201cIn order to fix the problem long term, we can\\u2019t just be the highlighter pen. We do a good job highlighting things, but we don\\u2019t do a great job of fixing things.\\\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2014/11/jason-chaffetz-house-oversight-113066_Page2.html#ixzz3ZYlpuBcK|title=Jason Chaffetz promises less personal oversight|first=Lauren|last=French|first2=John|last2=Bresnahan|publisher=''Politico''|date=November 20, 2014|accessdate=May 8, 2015}}</ref>\\n\\nChaffetz has reportedly built a strong relationship with his Democratic counterpart on the committee, Ranking Member [[Elijah Cummings]] (D-MD).  The two visited one another's districts the summer before Chaffetz became chairman of the committee. Chaffetz's visit to Baltimore was chronicled in the [http://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2014/07/06/7cd35f90-fd69-11e3-b1f4-8e77c632c07b_story.html Washington Post], [http://articles.baltimoresun.com/2014-06-23/news/bal-citing-a-new-era-cummings-hosts-chaffetz-in-baltimore-20140623_1_cummings-new-era-issa Baltimore Sun], and [http://www.sltrib.com/sltrib/politics/58124067-90/chaffetz-cummings-says-baltimore.html.csp Salt Lake Tribune].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2014/07/06/7cd35f90-fd69-11e3-b1f4-8e77c632c07b_story.html |title=House members try a DIY preemptive bipartisanship|first=Wesley|last=Lowery|publisher=''Washington Post''|date=July 6, 2014|accessdate=May 8, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/2014-06-23/news/bal-citing-a-new-era-cummings-hosts-chaffetz-in-baltimore-20140623_1_cummings-new-era-issa|title=Citing a 'new era,' Cummings hosts Chaffetz in Baltimore|first=John|last=Fritze|publisher=''Baltimore Sun''|date=June 23, 2014|accessdate=May 8, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sltrib.com/sltrib/politics/58124067-90/chaffetz-cummings-says-baltimore.html.csp|title=Utah Rep. Jason Chaffetz takes a tour of the liberal side|first=Thomas|last=Burr|publisher=''Salt Lake Tribune''|date=July 1, 2014|accessdate=May 8, 2015}}</ref> When Cummings visited Utah, Chaffetz took him to Moab, Utah where he was briefed on public lands issues before flying back to the State Capitol in Salt Lake City for a meeting with Governor Herbert and a tour of the [[The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints|LDS Church]]'s [[Welfare Square]].  That visit was extensively chronicled by [http://time.com/3084067/elijah-cummings-jason-chaffetz-darrell-issa-utah/ Time Magazine] and other news outlets.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://time.com/3084067/elijah-cummings-jason-chaffetz-darrell-issa-utah|title=Republican and Democratic Congressmen bond amid canyons and grouse|first=Alex|last=Rogers|publisher=''Time Magazine''|date=August 5, 2014|accessdate=May 8, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.deseretnews.com/article/865608073/Rep-Jason-Chaffetz-and-Maryland-Democrat-build-political-bridge-in-Utah.html?pg=all|title=Rep. Jason Chaffetz and Maryland Democrat build political bridge in Utah|first=Amy Joi|last=O'Donoghue|publisher=''Deseret News''|date=August 4, 2014|accessdate=May 8, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ksl.com/?sid=31000243|title= Chaffetz guides Maryland Democrat on tour of Utah lands|first=Amy Joi|last=O'Donoghue|publisher=''KSL''|date=August 4, 2015|accessdate=May 8, 2015}}</ref>\\n\\nUpon his ascension to chairmanship, Chaffetz committed to bringing a new level of bipartisan cooperation to the committee.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2014/11/18/chaffetz-tapped-to-succeed-issa-on-high-profile-house-oversight-panel/|title=Chaffetz tapped to succeed Issa on high profile House oversight panel|first=Nick|last=Kalman|publisher=''Fox News.com''|date=November 18, 2014|accessdate=May 8, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2014/11/Jason-Chaffetz-darrell-issa-chairman-Oversight-and-Government-Reform-Committee/382940/|title=Republicans appoint President Obama's next pain in the butt|first=Russell|last=Berman|publisher=''The Atlantic''|date=November 19, 2014|accessdate=May 8, 2015}}</ref>  That bipartisanship has played out in several investigations in which both Chaffetz and Cummings have been united in their calls for reform.  Among the issues that have drawn bipartisan support are the Secret Service investigation,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2015/02/04/politics/jason-chaffetz-oversight-obama/|title=Top Republican takes aim at Secret Service reform|first=Chris|last=Frates|publisher=''CNN.com''|date=February 4, 2015|accessdate=May 8, 2015}}</ref> the DEA prostitution scandal <ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/federal-eye/wp/2015/04/15/bipartisan-house-statement-expresses-lost-confidence-in-dea-chief/|title=Bipartisan House statement expresses lost confidence in DEA chief|first=Josh|last=Hicks|publisher=''Washington Post''|date=April 15, 2015|accessdate=May 8, 2015}}</ref> and the investigation into the US Chemical Safety Board.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://thehill.com/policy/energy-environment/236329-bipartisan-group-asks-obama-to-fire-chemical-agency-chief|title=Bipartisan group asks Obama to fire chemical agency chief|first=Timothy|last=Cama|publisher=''The Hill''|date=March 19, 2015|accessdate=May 8, 2015}}</ref>  Cummings told [http://thehill.com/homenews/house/239032-chaffetz-sets-sights-on-feds The Hill] in April 2015, \\u201cThe chairman\\u2019s leadership has been a sea change from the way the committee was run in the past, primarily because he has been willing to work with Democrats and because, for the most part, he has avoided overreaching.\\u201d<ref>{{cite news|url=http://thehill.com/homenews/house/239032-chaffetz-sets-sights-on-feds |title=Chaffetz sets sights on feds|first=Cristina|last=Marcos|publisher=''The Hill''|date=April 16, 2015|accessdate=May 8, 2015}}</ref>\\n\\n===Elections===\\n====2008====\\n{{Main|United States House of Representatives elections in Utah, 2008#District 3}}\\n\\nOn January 1, 2007, before the 110th Congress was sworn in, Jason Chaffetz announced that he was \\\"testing the waters\\\" for a Congressional run against six-term incumbent, [[Chris Cannon]], for the Republican nomination in this heavily Republican district.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://archive.sltrib.com/article.php?id=4934937&itype=NGPSID|title=Ex-Huntsman staffer may battle Cannon|first=Jennifer W.|last=Sanchez|publisher=''Salt Lake Tribune''|date=January 2, 2007|accessdate=May 8, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.heraldextra.com/news/governor-s-ex-chief-of-staff-considers-run-for-rd/article_d03a0bb2-1a27-5511-bec6-f91e3cc84927.html |title=Governor's ex-chief of staff considers run for 3rd District|first=Alan|last=Choate|publisher=''Daily Herald''|date=January 1, 2007|accessdate=May 8, 2015}}</ref>  Nine months later, on October 1, 2007, Chaffetz formally entered the race for the Republican nomination.  That same day, David Leavitt issued a press release announcing his campaign had raised $100,000 to challenge Cannon.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://archive.sltrib.com/printfriendly.php?id=7053373&itype=NGPSID|title=Two Republicans challenge Congressman Chris Cannon|first1=Dan|last1=Robert|first2=Robert|last2=Gehrke|publisher=''Salt Lake Tribune''|date=October 1, 2007|accessdate=May 8, 2015}}</ref>  Leavitt, brother to popular 3-term Utah Governor and Bush Administration cabinet member [[Mike Leavitt]], more than doubled Chaffetz in fundraising for that quarter.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.deseretnews.com/article/print/695220726/Money-no-problem-for-GOPs-Leavitt.html|title=Money no problem for GOP's Leavitt|first=Bob|last=Bernick, Jr.|publisher=''Deseret News''|date=October 22, 2007|accessdate=May 8, 2015}}</ref> A March 2008 Deseret News/KSL TV poll by Dan Jones & Associates released two days before the party caucuses showed Jason Chaffetz with 4% support.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.deseretnews.com/article/695263930/Cannon-facing-a-tough-contest.html?pg=all|title=Cannon facing a tough contest|first=Suzanne|last=Struglinski|publisher=''Deseret News''|date=March 23, 2008|accessdate=May 8, 2015}}</ref>\\n\\nAfter the nearly 1200 3rd District delegates were elected on March 25, 2008, Chaffetz sent a mailer announcing that he would run a different kind of campaign.  He would have no paid staff, no campaign office, no free meals for delegates, no campaign debt and no polling.  He committed to spend between $70 and $80 per delegate, telling voters, \\\"How you run your campaign is indicative of how you're going to be in office.\\\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://archive.sltrib.com/article.php?id=8667378&itype=NGPSID|title=Utah caucuses:delegates are a force to reckon with|first=Cathy|last=McKitrick|publisher=''Salt Lake Tribune''|date=March 23, 2008|accessdate=May 8, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.deseretnews.com/article/695275337/Cannon-fails-to-file-reports-on-finances.html?pg=all|title=Cannon fails to file reports on finances|first=Catherine|last=Smith|publisher=''Deseret News''|date=May 1, 2008|accessdate=May 8, 2015}}</ref>\\n\\nAlthough Cannon was one of the most conservative members of the House, Chaffetz ran to his right. He said that Cannon \\u201chas failed us for not instituting conservative principles\\\", consistently calling for a return to the core conservative principles of fiscal discipline, limited government, accountability and a strong national defense. He campaigned on stronger measures to fix legal immigration and remove the incentives for [[illegal immigration]], an issue he continued to press throughout the campaign.<ref name=\\\"NYT-7Jun2007\\\"/><ref>{{cite news |title=Cannon tough on Immigration? |publisher=''[[Deseret News]]'' |date=June 17, 2008 |last1=Davidson |first1=Lee |last2=Bulkeley |first2=Deborah |page=B1}}</ref> The week before the convention, David Leavitt told the Salt Lake Tribune, \\\"If Jason Chaffetz beats me [at the convention], Chris Cannon will be the congressman.  Jason Chaffetz has no resources, no organization.\\\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://archive.sltrib.com/article.php?id=9200982&itype=NGPSID|title=Cannon facing a challenge|first=Robert|last=Gehrke|publisher=''Salt Lake Tribune''|date=May 9, 2008|accessdate=May 8, 2015}}</ref>\\n\\nAt the May 10, 2008 Utah Republican State Convention Chaffetz won 59% of the 3rd District's delegates to Leavitt's 41%.  He came a few hundred votes short of tallying 60% of the delegates and winning the nomination without a primary.<ref>{{cite news |first=Frank |last=Pignanelli |title=Chaffetz has a shot at defeating Cannon |publisher=''[[Deseret News]]'' |date=May 18, 2008 |page=G1}}</ref>\\n\\nIn the primary, polls showed a close race.  A Dan Jones poll released on May 22, 2008, showed Cannon leading Chaffetz 39 percent to 37 percent among likely voters.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.deseretnews.com/article/700227979/Race-tight-between-Chaffetz-and-Cannon.html?pg=all|title=Race tight between Chaffetz and Cannon|first=Bob|last=Bernick, Jr.|publisher=''Deseret News''|date=May 22, 2008|accessdate=May 8, 2015}}</ref> A subsequent poll released June 21 showed a statistical tie, favoring Cannon 44\\u201340 with a 5.5% margin of error.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.deseretnews.com/article/700236617/Cannon-Chaffetz-in-a-tie.html?pg=all |title=Cannon, Chaffetz in a tie|first=Bob|last=Bernick, Jr.|publisher=''Deseret News''|date=June 21, 2008|accessdate=May 8, 2015}}</ref>  On June 24, 2008, Chaffetz defeated Cannon by a vote of 60% to 40%.<ref>{{cite news |first=Tad |last=Walch |url=http://deseretnews.com/article/1,5143,700237809,00.html |title=Chaffetz wins big \\u2013 He turns Cannon into a lame duck |publisher=''[[Deseret News]]'' |date=June 25, 2008 |accessdate=November 18, 2011}}</ref> It was considered an upset victory as Cannon was endorsed by [[George W. Bush]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://deseretnews.com/article/1,5143,695276748,00.html |title=Bush sends letter endorsing Cannon |publisher=''[[Deseret News]]'' |date=May 6, 2008 |accessdate=November 18, 2011}}</ref> the state's two U.S. Senators [[Orrin Hatch]] and [[Bob Bennett (politician)|Bob Bennett]], and nearly all of the state Republican establishment. Cannon also outspent Chaffetz by 6 to 1.<ref>{{cite news |first=Joe |last=Pyrah |url=http://heraldextra.com/content/view/271526/999999/ |title=Chaffetz defeats Cannon |publisher=''[[Daily Herald (Utah)|Daily Herald]]'' |date=June 25, 2008 |accessdate=November 18, 2011}}</ref>  Cannon's primary defeat spurred worry among Republican incumbents.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.sltrib.com/article.php?id=9697237&itype=NGPSID |title=Incumbent fear: Cannon loss sets off wave of worry |first1=Thomas |last1=Burr |first2=Robert |last2=Gehrke |date=June 26, 2008 |work=The Salt Lake Tribune |accessdate=October 12, 2015}}</ref>\\n\\nChaffetz faced Democrat [[Bennion Spencer]] in the 2008 general election, along with Jim Noorlander of the [[Constitution Party (United States)|Constitution Party]].  Chaffetz's firm position against asking for earmarks created some controversy during the general election campaign.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://archive.sltrib.com/article.php?id=9840877&itype=NGPSID|title=Earmark backlash could cost Utah millions|publisher=''Salt Lake Tribune''|date=July 10, 2008|accessdate=May 8, 2015}}</ref>  Chaffetz said, \\\"Until there's reform, I will not ask for them.  They're a cancer within the system and I want to extract them.\\\" Ultimately, Chaffetz won election with 66% of the vote.  However, he had effectively clinched a seat in Congress when he won the Republican nomination.  The 3rd is one of the most Republican districts in the nation; in 2008 it had a [[Cook Partisan Voting Index]] of R+26.\\n\\n====2010====\\n{{Main|United States House of Representatives elections in Utah, 2010#District 3}}\\n\\nChaffetz defeated Democratic nominee Karen Hyer and all third-party candidates, garnering 72% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.deseretnews.com/election/2/2010-Utah-General-election.html |title=2010 Utah General Election Results: Federal Offices \\u2013 House |publisher=''[[Deseret News]]''|accessdate=November 18, 2011}}</ref>  The ''Salt Lake Tribune'', often critical of Chaffetz, endorsed him in the race, writing, \\\"U.S. Rep. Jason Chaffetz, R-Utah, has delivered as advertised for Utah's 3rd District.\\\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://archive.sltrib.com/article.php?id=11493184&itype=storyID|title=Jason Chaffetz: Congressman deserves second term|author=Salt Lake Tribune editorial board|publisher=''Salt Lake Tribune''|date=October 18, 2010|accessdate=May 8, 2015}}</ref>\\n\\n====2012====\\n{{Main|United States House of Representatives elections in Utah, 2012#District 3}}\\n\\nIn early 2012 Chaffetz worked as a representative of the [[Mitt Romney presidential campaign, 2012|Mitt Romney presidential campaign]] during [[Republican Party presidential primaries, 2012|primary season]], shadowing the campaign of rival GOP candidate [[Newt Gingrich]] to offer rebuttals to reporters following Gingrich speeches.<ref>Shawna Shepherd (January 27, 2012), [http://politicalticker.blogs.cnn.com/2012/01/27/romney-surrogates-shadow-gingrich-campaign/ \\\"Romney surrogates shadow Gingrich campaign\\\"] ''[[CNN]]''</ref> \\\"I'm just trying to offer a little perspective,\\\" said Chaffetz at one of Gingrich's Florida stops.<ref>Jane Musgrave (January 27, 2012), [http://www.palmbeachpost.com/news/republican-jewish-coalition-turns-out-in-force-for-2130653.html \\\"Republican Jewish Coalition turns out in force for Gingrich in Delray\\\"]  ''[[The Palm Beach Post]]''</ref>\\n\\n===Tenure===\\nChaffetz announced at the start of the congressional term, in 2009, that he would be sleeping on a cot in his office, rather than renting a [[Washington, D.C.]] apartment.<ref name=\\\"sleeping office\\\">{{cite news| last = Karl| first = Jonathan| coauthor = | title =Freshman Congressman Sleeps on Cot| publisher =''[[ABC News]]'' | date =January 6, 2009| url =http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/story?id=6587327&page=1| accessdate =January 9, 2009 }}</ref> Chaffetz said, \\\"I'm trying to live the example that it doesn't take big dollars in order to get where we want to go. I can save my family $1,500 a month by sleeping on a cot in my office as opposed to getting a fancy place that's maybe a little bit more comfortable.\\\"<ref name=\\\"sleeping office\\\"/> His family will continue to live in [[Alpine, Utah|Alpine]]. \\\"We are now $10 trillion in debt. $10 trillion. Those are expenses that have to be paid at some point\\\", he said. If he can tighten his belt in these tough economic times, Chaffetz said, Congress should be able to as well.<ref name=\\\"sleeping office\\\"/>\\n\\nChaffetz appeared on the \\\"Better Know A District\\\" segment of ''[[The Colbert Report]]'' on January 6, 2009, where he was defeated by [[Stephen Colbert]] in leg wrestling.<ref>{{cite web|title=Better Know a District \\u2013 Utah's 3rd \\u2013 Jason Chaffetz|work=Colbert Nation |url=http://www.colbertnation.com/the-colbert-report-videos/215400/january-06-2009/better-know-a-district---utah-s-3rd---jason-chaffetz |date=January 6, 2009 |accessdate=November 18, 2011}}</ref>\\n\\n====Cut, Cap and Balance Act====\\nIn June 2011, Chaffetz sponsored HR 2560,  the [[Cut, Cap, and Balance Act]] of 2011. HR 2560 capped FY 2012 discretionary appropriations at $1.019 trillion, which was $31 billion below FY 2011 discretionary spending, and provided $126.5 billion for war spending. HR 2560 imposed a cap of $681 billion on \\\"other\\\" mandatory spending. Excluded from the $681 billion cap were [[Social Security (United States)|Social Security]], [[Medicare (United States)|Medicare]], veterans programs, and interest payments. [[HR 2560]] gradually reduced federal government spending as a percent of gross domestic product from 24.1% in 2011<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cbo.gov/sites/default/files/cbofiles/attachments/08-22-2012-Update_to_Outlook.pdf |title=An Update to the Budget and Economic Outlook: Fiscal Years 2012 to 2022 |work=Congressional Budget Office |date=August 22, 2012 |accessdate=October 12, 2015}}</ref> to 21.7% in 2013 and 19.9% in 2021. HR 2560 also allowed for an increase in the debt ceiling of $2.4 trillion, as requested by [[President Obama]], conditioned upon approval by both Houses of Congress of a qualifying Balanced Budget Amendment which would then be sent to the states for approval. HR 2560 passed the [[United States House of Representatives|House of Representatives]] but was rejected by the Senate.<ref>http://rsc.jordan.house.gov/uploadedfiles/lb_71811_cutcapbalance-4.pdf {{dead link|date=October 2015}}</ref>\\n\\n====Social Security reform====\\nIn November 2011, Chaffetz announced a seven-point Social Security proposal.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://chaffetz.house.gov/sites/chaffetz.house.gov/files/SS%20Press%20Release%20with%20Maya%20Quote.pdf |title=Chaffetz Announces Social Security Reform Proposals |work=chaffetz.house.gov |accessdate=October 12, 2015}}</ref> The seven provisions include using a chained [[CPI-W]] for calculating annual [[COLAs]], increasing normal retirement age, adding progressive price indexing to primary insurance amount calculations, means-testing benefits for high income beneficiaries, increasing the number of years for calculating average indexed monthly earnings, indexing special minimum benefits to wages instead of [[CPI]], and increasing benefits by 5% for retirees when they reach age 85.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://chaffetz.house.gov/sites/chaffetz.house.gov/files/ChaffetzLetterFinal.pdf |title=Letter to The Honorable Jason Chaffetz |work=Office of the Chief Actuary |date=November 9, 2011 |accessdate=October 12, 2015}}</ref>\\n\\n====President Obama====\\nIn January 2010, Chaffetz was called upon to question President Obama at a meeting of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]] Conference.<ref>{{cite av media |url=http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QHO6MaIG60g |title=Chaffetz Questions Obama |date=January 29, 2010 |work=YouTube |accessdate=October 12, 2015}}</ref>  Chaffetz applauded Obama for some of the promises made during the campaign, but asked why promises to broadcast healthcare debates on [[CSPAN]], keep lobbyists out of senior positions, go line-by-line through the health care bill and end earmarks had not been kept.  Video of the Q&A went viral and received extensive media coverage.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.deseretnews.com/article/print/700005678/Utahs-Jason-Chaffetz-tells-Obama-face-to-face-that-he-broke-promises.html |title=Utah's Jason Chaffetz tells Obama face to face that he broke promises |first=Lee |last=Davidson |date= |work=Deseret News |accessdate=October 12, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sltrib.com/news/ci_14295472 |title=Chaffetz goes toe to toe with Obama |first=Matt |last=Canham |date=January 29, 2010 |work=The Salt Lake Tribune |accessdate=October 12, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,584410,00.html | work=Fox News | title=Meet the Congressman Who Confronted President Obama | date=January 31, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite av media |url=http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OLtVRBCsnOc |title=CNN_01-29-2010 Campbell Brown Interview Part 1 |date=February 1, 2010 |work=YouTube |accessdate=October 12, 2015}}</ref> Upon hearing that U.S. President [[Barack Obama]] won the [[Nobel Peace Prize]] on October 9, 2009, Chaffetz said he had \\\"lost all respect for the award\\\", saying \\\"it used to be one of distinction, but [now] it is hard to give it any credibility\\\".<ref name=\\\"Obama Peace Prize\\\">{{cite news| last = Canham| first = Matt| coauthor = | title = Republicans Incredulous, Critical over Obama's Peace Prize| publisher = ''[[The Salt Lake Tribune]]''| date = October 10, 2009| url = http://www.sltrib.com/ci_13525370?IADID| accessdate = November 12, 2009}}</ref>\\n\\n====Nuclear waste====\\nIn November 2009 Chaffetz co-sponsored a bill in the House with Rep. Jim Matheson to block the importation of foreign nuclear waste into the United States, putting him directly at odds with Rep. [[Rob Bishop]] and Utah's Senators Bennett and Hatch, who had historically supported importing foreign nuclear waste into Utah with restrictions.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://chaffetz.house.gov/press-release/chaffetz-supports-rid-act |title=Chaffetz Supports The RID Act |work=chaffetz.house.gov |accessdate=October 12, 2015}}</ref>\\n\\n====Homeland security====\\nIn December 2009, Chaffetz championed legislation to limit the use of full-body imaging scanners at airports unless a metal detector first indicated a need for more screening. The images have come under intense scrutiny from privacy groups for allegedly letting security administrators view images of undressed passengers.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?file=/c/a/2009/12/29/MNF61BAGT9.DTL|title=Do airport imagers invade privacy? |last=Asimov |first=Nanette |publisher=''[[The San Francisco Chronicle]]'' |date=December 29, 2009 |accessdate=November 18, 2011}}</ref>\\n\\nChaffetz and TSA have had a rocky relationship since he joined Congress. In his freshman year, in what critics have described as political grandstanding, he accused [[Transportation Security Administration]] (TSA) agents at his hometown airport in [[Salt Lake City]] of unfairly targeting him to pass through a full-body scanning machine\\u2014a device Chaffetz believes is invasive. The Republican lawmaker said he believed he was targeted partially for his opposition to granting TSA screeners collective bargaining rights. A FOIA request by the [[Deseret News]] for video of the incident showed it to be a \\\"tame and rather civilized exchange between the two.\\\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.deseretnews.com/article/705337424/No-fracas-shown-in-TSA-video.html?pg=all|title=No fracas show in TSA video |last=Davidson |first=Lee|publisher=''[[The Deseret News]]'' |date=October 18, 2009 |accessdate=May 8, 2015}}</ref> TSA's November 2009 report following their internal investigation primarily supported the Chaffetz version of the story.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.deseretnews.com/article/705342395/TSA-backs-up-most-of-Chaffetzs-account.html?pg=all |title=TSA backs up most of Chaffetz's account |last=Davidson |first=Lee |publisher=''[[The Deseret News]]'' |date=November 6, 2009 |accessdate=May 8, 2015}}</ref> The union representing some of the officers said at the time that agents followed proper procedure and that an officer who had recently returned from military service in Iraq didn\\u2019t recognize Chaffetz.<ref>{{cite news |newspaper=Washington Post |title=Bill Requires TSA Seek Parental OK Before Patting-Down A Child. |date=April 19, 2011 |url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/federal-eye/post/bill-requires-tsa-seek-parental-ok-before-patting-down-a-child/2011/04/19/AF0dj03D_blog.html}}</ref>\\n\\n====Afghanistan====\\nChaffetz criticized the surge of 30,000 troops President Obama authorized for the war in Afghanistan, saying that the United States does not have a clear policy or exit strategy.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/07/12/AR2010071205394.html | work=The Washington Post | first=Perry | last=Bacon Jr | title=Freshman lawmaker Jason Chaffetz goes against Republican grain on Afghan war | date=July 13, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/1109/29962.html |title=Chaffetz: Bring home Afghan troops |first=Daniel |last=Libit |date=November 29, 2009 |work=POLITICO |accessdate=October 12, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://chaffetz.house.gov/press-release/chairman-chaffetz-questions-sigar-afghanistan-transparency |title=Chairman Chaffetz questions SIGAR on Afghanistan Transparency |work=chaffetz.house.gov |accessdate=October 12, 2015}}</ref>\\n\\n====Benghazi attack====\\nChaffetz has been vocal against the White House and State Department's handling of the attacks on the US Consulate compound. The Administration first stated the attacks were sparked by a spontaneous protest, then later stated the violence was a planned terrorist attack.\\n:\\\"There was a very conscious decision made, I believe\\u2014my personal opinion is that they wanted the appearance of 'normalization' there in Libya and building up of an infrastructure, putting up barbed wire on our facility would lead to the wrong impression. Something that this administration didn\\u2019t want to have moving forward.\\\"<ref name=\\\"thehill.com\\\">{{cite web |last=Meghashyam |first=Mali |title=Chaffetz Suspects Libya Security Decisions \\u2018coordinated\\u2019 Between White House, State Dept. |date=October 19, 2012 |url=http://thehill.com/video/house/260927-chaffetz-suspects-libya-security-decisions-coordinated-between-white-house-state-dept |work=thehill.com}}</ref>\\n\\nHe criticized [[United States Ambassador to the United Nations|US ambassador to the United Nations]] [[Susan Rice|Susan Rice\\u2019s]] initial comments calling them \\u201csomewhere between an outrageous lie and total falsehood.\\u201d<ref name=\\\"thehill.com\\\"/>\\n\\nChaffetz has been criticized for politicizing the Benghazi incident, acknowledging in an interview with [[CNN]] anchor [[Soledad O'Brien]] that he had \\\"voted to cut the funding for embassy security\\\" and that House Republicans had consciously voted to reduce the funds allocated to the State Department for embassy security since winning the majority in 2010. \\\"Absolutely,\\\" he said. \\\"Look, we have to make priorities and choices in this country.\\\"<ref>{{cite web |work=Huffington Post |title=Jason Chaffetz Admits House GOP Cut Funding For Embassy Security: 'You Have To Prioritize Things.' |date=October 10, 2012 |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/10/10/jason-chaffetz-embassy_n_1954912.html}}</ref>\\n\\n====Resolutions====\\nChaffetz pledged to vote against what he calls \\\"trivial resolutions,\\\" including those dealing with sports, such as congratulating the winning team of the [[Super Bowl]]. Chaffetz feels that the House could be taking up more important legislation.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/dc/2010/07/norton_gets_in_heated_house_fl.html|title=Norton gets in heated House floor dispute ... over a New York racetrack?|accessdate=July 21, 2010|last=Pershing|first=Ben|date=July 21, 2010|work=[[The Washington Post]]}}</ref>\\n\\n====Protection for greater sage grouse====\\nChaffetz has opposed federal protection for Utah's resident [[Sage Grouse|greater sage grouse]], a bird whose population has shrunk from 16 million 100 years ago to about 200,000 today. In 2007, a court ruled that political tampering by [[Julie A. MacDonald]], then-deputy assistant secretary for the [[United States Fish and Wildlife Service]], had \\\"tainted\\\" the bird's assessment, and a new review was ordered. In March 2010, [[United States Secretary of the Interior|U.S. interior secretary]] [[Ken Salazar]] assigned the bird \\\"warranted but precluded\\\" status, paving the way for its future protection.<ref name=nyt3610>{{cite news |url=http://www.nytimes.com/2010/03/06/science/earth/06grouse.html?partner=rss&emc=rss |title=No Endangered Status for Plains Bird |publisher=''[[The New York Times]]'' |last=Broder |first=John |date=March 6, 2010 |accessdate=November 18, 2011}}</ref>\\n\\n====D.C. cannabis reform====\\nIn February 2015, Chaffetz threatened [[Mayor of the District of Columbia|Washington, D.C. mayor]] [[Muriel Bowser]] with possible jail time if she implemented [[Initiative 71]]. The ballot initiative would legalize small amounts of cannabis in the district and was approved by about 64.87 percent of the voters in 2014.<ref name=CannabisDC>{{cite web|last1=McCabe|first1=David|title=Republican threatens DC mayor with jail over marijuana law|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/blog-briefing-room/news/233778-republican-threatens-dc-mayor-with-jail-over-marijuana-law|publisher=The Hill|accessdate=February 25, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ballotpedia.org/Washington_D.C._Marijuana_Legalization,_Initiative_71_%28November_2014%29|title=Washington D.C. Marijuana Legalization, Initiative 71 (November 2014)|publisher=Ballotpedia|accessdate=February 25, 2015}}</ref>\\n\\n====Planned Parenthood hearings====\\nIn a September 2015 hearing, Chaffetz questioned [[Planned Parenthood]]'s president [[Cecile Richards]] on her salary,<ref name=PlannedParentSalary>{{cite web|title=GOP chair attacks Planned Parenthood president's salary|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2015/09/planned-parenthood-jason-chaffetz-no-funding-214219|publisher=Politico|accessdate=October 5, 2015}}</ref> and displayed a chart he claimed was taken from Planned Parenthood's annual report, but sources confirm the claim the chart was actually taken from Americans United for Life chart data that was manipulated using questionable dual-axis charting methodologies. Experts in data presentation said this was an egregious example of using a chart to mislead.<ref name=PlannedParentChart2>{{cite web|title=Chart shown at Planned Parenthood hearing is misleading and 'ethically wrong'|url=http://www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/statements/2015/oct/01/jason-chaffetz/chart-shown-planned-parenthood-hearing-misleading-/|publisher=Politifact|accessdate=October 5, 2015}}</ref>\\n\\n====Speakership election====\\n{{main|Speaker of the United States House of Representatives election, October 2015}}\\nFollowing [[John Boehner]]'s announcement that he would resign from Congress, Chaffetz declared his candidacy to replace him as [[Speaker of the United States House of Representatives|Speaker of the House]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2015/10/04/politics/jason-chaffetz-kevin-mccarthy-house-speaker/|title=Jason Chaffetz challenges Kevin McCarthy for speaker |first=Eric |last=Bradner|work=CNN|date=October 4, 2015|accessdate=October 8, 2015}}</ref>\\n\\n===Committee assignments===\\n* '''[[United States House Committee on the Judiciary|Committee on the Judiciary]]'''\\n** [[United States House Judiciary Subcommittee on Intellectual Property, Competition, and the Internet|Subcommittee on Intellectual Property, Competition, and the Internet]]\\n** [[United States House Judiciary Subcommittee on Crime, Terrorism, and Homeland Security|Subcommittee on Crime, Terrorism, and Homeland Security]]\\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Oversight and Government Reform|Committee on Oversight and Government Reform]]''' (chairman)\\n** [[United States House Oversight Subcommittee on Federal Workforce, U.S. Postal Service and Labor Policy|Subcommittee on Federal Workforce, U.S. Postal Service and Labor Policy]]\\n** [[United States House Oversight Subcommittee on National Security, Homeland Defense and Foreign Operations|Subcommittee on National Security, Homeland Defense and Foreign Operations]] (chairman)\\n** [[United States House Oversight Subcommittee on Technology, Information Policy, Intergovernmental Relations and Procurement Reform|Subcommittee on Technology, Information Policy, Intergovernmental Relations and Procurement Reform]]\\n\\n==References==\\n{{reflist|30em}}\\n\\n==External links==\\n* [http://chaffetz.house.gov/ Congressman Jason Chaffetz] official U.S. House site\\n* [http://www.jasonforcongress.com/ Jason Chaffetz for Congress]\\n* {{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Utah/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Jason_Chaffetz_%5BR-3%5D}}\\n* {{C-SPAN|jasonchaffetz}}\\n* {{CongLinks | congbio = C001076 | ballot = Jason_Chaffetz | nndb = 594/000180054 | votesmart = 103482 | govtrack = 412270 | opencong = 412270 | rollcall = 28868 | politifact = jason-chaffetz | fec = H8UT03089 | opensecrets = N00028958 | assets = jason-chaffetz | legistorm = 983/Rep_Jason_Chaffetz.html | followthemoney = | ontheissues = House/Jason_Chaffetz.htm | congress = jason-chaffetz/1956 | worldcat = | c-span = jasonchaffetz | imdb = 3064737 | bloomberg = jason-chaffetz | nyt = | wsj = | washpo = gIQAm9WMAP }}\\n* [http://www.sltrib.com/Topics/CHAFFETZ Collected news and commentary] at ''[[The Salt Lake Tribune]]''\\n\\n{{s-start}}\\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\\n{{s-bef|before=[[Chris Cannon]]}}\\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[List of United States Representatives from Utah|U.S. House of Representatives]]<br>from [[Utah's 3rd congressional district]]|years=2009\\u2013present}}\\n{{s-inc|rows=2}}\\n|-\\n{{s-bef|before=[[Darrell Issa]]}}\\n{{s-ttl|title=Chairman of the [[United States House Committee on Oversight and Government Reform|House Committee on Oversight and Government Reform]]|years=2015\\u2013present}}\\n|-\\n{{s-prec|usa}}\\n{{s-bef|before=[[Mark Sanford]]}}\\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of current members of the United States House of Representatives by seniority|United States Representatives by seniority]]|years=196th}}\\n{{s-aft|after=[[Mike Coffman]]}}\\n{{s-end}}\\n\\n{{UT-FedRep}}\\n{{USHouseCurrent}}\\n{{UtahUSRepresenatives}}\\n\\n{{Persondata <!-- Metadata: see [[Wikipedia:Persondata]]. -->\\n| NAME              =Chaffetz, Jason\\n| ALTERNATIVE NAMES =\\n| SHORT DESCRIPTION =American politician\\n| DATE OF BIRTH     =March 26, 1967\\n| PLACE OF BIRTH    =[[Los Gatos, California]], U.S.\\n| DATE OF DEATH     =\\n| PLACE OF DEATH    =\\n}}\\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chaffetz, Jason}}\\n[[Category:1967 births]]\\n[[Category:American anti\\u2013illegal immigration activists]]\\n[[Category:American football placekickers]]\\n[[Category:American Latter Day Saints]]\\n[[Category:American people of Jewish descent]]\\n[[Category:BYU Cougars football players]]\\n[[Category:Converts to Mormonism from Judaism]]\\n[[Category:Living people]]\\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from Utah]]\\n[[Category:People from Alpine, Utah]]\\n[[Category:People from Santa Clara County, California]]\\n[[Category:Players of American football from California]]\\n[[Category:Republican Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]\\n[[Category:Utah Republicans]]\"}]}}}}"